      <form action="dashboard">

       <div class="govuk-form-group">
            <h1 class="govuk-label-wrapper">
                <label class="govuk-label govuk-label--l" for="event-name">
                Lesson plan for year 8s on Romans
                </label>
            </h1>
            
            
                <section>
                <h2 class="govuk-heading-m" style="margin-top:50px;">Lesson 1: Introduction to Ancient Rome</h2>
                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>Objective:</strong> Students will understand the key aspects of Roman civilization.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>1. Engagement (15 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">Start with a brief discussion on what students know about ancient Rome. Use visual aids like maps, images, or short video clips to capture their interest. Ask open-ended questions to prompt students' prior knowledge and encourage participation.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>2. Introduction to Roman Republic (20 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">Provide an overview of the Roman Republic, including its formation, government structure, and the concept of checks and balances. Use simple diagrams or charts to illustrate the Roman political system.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>3. Activity - Create a Roman Timeline (25 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">Students work individually or in pairs to create a timeline of key events in Roman history. Encourage the inclusion of significant dates, events, and achievements.</p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Lesson 2: Daily Life in Ancient Rome</h2>
                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>Objective:</strong> Students will understand the social structure and daily life in ancient Rome.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>1. Recap (15 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">Briefly review the previous lesson and address any questions or concerns students may have.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>2. Introduction to Roman Society (20 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">Discuss the social structure of ancient Rome, highlighting the roles of citizens, slaves, and different classes. Explore aspects of daily life, including housing, food, clothing, and entertainment.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>3. Activity - Roman Villa Design (25 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">Students engage in a creative activity where they design a Roman villa, considering the layout, rooms, and amenities. Emphasize the social status reflected in their designs.</p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Lesson 3: Roman Culture and Legacy</h2>
                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>Objective:</strong> Students will explore Roman culture, achievements, and their lasting impact.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>1. Recap (15 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">Review key points from the previous lessons and clarify any misconceptions.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>2. Introduction to Roman Culture (20 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">Explore aspects of Roman art, literature, architecture, and engineering. Showcase examples of Roman achievements and their lasting impact on Western culture.</p>

                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>3. Activity - Roman Innovations Poster (25 mins):</strong></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">In groups, students create posters highlighting Roman innovations and their contributions to society. Encourage creativity and effective communication in their presentations.</p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Assessment:</h2>
                <p class="govuk-body"><strong>Homework Assignment:</strong> Students write a short essay reflecting on the enduring legacy of ancient Rome and its influence on the modern world.</p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Conclusion:</h2>
                <p class="govuk-body">Conclude the unit by discussing the lasting impact of the Romans on today's society. Encourage students to connect their learning to present-day culture, politics, and architecture.</p>
            </section>

        </div>

